<section class="section" style="background:var(--off-white);">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="accessibility-wrap">

      <div class="accessibility-highlight">
        <span class="eyebrow blue">Simple Summary</span>
        <h2>We want everyone to be able to use this website</h2>
        <p>RVRA is a community organisation, and our website should reflect that. We aim to make our content clear, easy to navigate, and accessible across different devices, browsers, and assistive technologies.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>1. Our commitment</h2>
        <p>Roe Valley Residents Association wants its website to be accessible to as many people as possible. This means you should be able to:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>zoom in without the text becoming unreadable;</li>
          <li>navigate the website using a keyboard;</li>
          <li>use the website with screen readers and assistive technologies;</li>
          <li>read content that uses clear headings, meaningful links, and simple language;</li>
          <li>access the website on mobile, tablet, laptop, and desktop devices.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>2. Accessibility standard we aim for</h2>
        <p>Where reasonably possible, we aim to follow the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines, known as WCAG. These guidelines are internationally recognised recommendations for making web content more accessible.</p>
        <p>Our aim is to work towards WCAG 2.2 Level AA, while continuing to improve the website over time.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>3. What we have done to support accessibility</h2>
        <div class="accessibility-check-grid">
          <div class="accessibility-check">
            <strong>Clear structure</strong>
            <p>Pages use headings, sections, and navigation links to make content easier to scan.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="accessibility-check">
            <strong>Readable design</strong>
            <p>The site uses large text, generous spacing, and strong colour contrast across most page sections.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="accessibility-check">
            <strong>Keyboard access</strong>
            <p>Links, buttons, menus, and form fields are designed to be reachable without a mouse.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="accessibility-check">
            <strong>Helpful image text</strong>
            <p>Images and placeholders include alternative text where they communicate useful information.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>4. Known limitations</h2>
        <p>This website is still being developed and improved. We have not yet completed a formal external accessibility audit.</p>
        <p>Known or possible limitations include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>some older pages may not yet fully match the newest site structure;</li>
          <li>some images may still need more descriptive alternative text once final photos are added;</li>
          <li>embedded third-party content, social media links, or external websites may not be fully controlled by RVRA;</li>
          <li>some downloadable documents, if added in future, may need separate accessibility checks.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>We will continue reviewing and improving the website as content is updated.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>5. Forms and online enquiries</h2>
        <p>Some pages may include enquiry or self-referral forms. We aim to make these forms clear, labelled, and easy to use.</p>
        <p>If a form does not work for you, or if you would prefer to contact us another way, please phone or email us using the details below.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>6. Alternative formats</h2>
        <p>If you need information from this website in a different format, please contact us. For example, you can ask for information to be explained over the phone, sent by email, or provided in a simpler format where possible.</p>
        <div class="accessibility-contact-grid">
          <div class="accessibility-contact-item">
            <strong>Email</strong>
            <a href="mailto:info@rvra.org.uk">info@rvra.org.uk</a>
          </div>
          <div class="accessibility-contact-item">
            <strong>Phone</strong>
            <a href="tel:02877769996">028 7776 9996</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>7. Reporting an accessibility problem</h2>
        <p>If you find an accessibility problem on this website, please let us know so we can look into it.</p>
        <p>When contacting us, it helps if you can tell us:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>which page you were using;</li>
          <li>what went wrong;</li>
          <li>what device, browser, or assistive technology you were using, if relevant;</li>
          <li>what you were trying to do.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>We will do our best to respond and fix issues where reasonably possible.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>8. Legal context</h2>
        <p>All UK service providers have duties to make reasonable adjustments for disabled people. In Northern Ireland, disability discrimination law also applies to service providers.</p>
        <p>RVRA is not presenting this page as a formal public sector accessibility statement, but we are using accessibility guidance as a practical standard for improving the website.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="accessibility-card">
        <h2>9. Ongoing improvements</h2>
        <p>Accessibility is not a one-time task. As the website grows, we will keep checking:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>colour contrast;</li>
          <li>keyboard navigation;</li>
          <li>mobile layout;</li>
          <li>image alt text;</li>
          <li>form labels and error messages;</li>
          <li>page headings and link text.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This statement will be updated when major changes are made to the website.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

